echo
The echo command does one simple job: it prints to the output the argument passed to it.

This example:

Bash
echo "hello"
will print hello to the terminal.

We can append the output to a file:

Bash
echo "hello" >> output.txt
We can interpolate environment variables:

Bash
echo "The path variable is $PATH"
💡 Extra Context on echo and Redirection
Like we saw with the date command earlier, echo pairs perfectly with redirection operators:

Overwrite (>): Wipes output.txt and sets its content exactly to "hello".

Bash
echo "hello" > output.txt
Append (>>): Leaves the existing lines in output.txt completely alone and drops "hello" down as a brand-new line at the bottom. This is the classic way to quickly write code or configuration lines into a file without booting up a full text editor like nano or vim.